# Multi-stage Dockerfiles — why, samples, size, and “faster” containers

## 1. What multi-stage is

A **multi-stage** Dockerfile has **more than one `FROM`**. Earlier stages install compilers, headers, and build tools. The **final stage** copies **only** what you need to run (binaries, static assets, a slim runtime). Stages you don’t `COPY` from are discarded in the **final image** (their layers are not part of the published image).

A **normal (single-stage)** Dockerfile uses **one** `FROM` and often leaves **build dependencies** inside the image you ship — bigger image, larger attack surface, slower **pulls**.

---

## 2. Why multi-stage is “better” than a normal Dockerfile

| Topic | Single-stage (typical mistake) | Multi-stage |
|-------|--------------------------------|-------------|
| **Image size** | Full JDK/Go toolchain, `gcc`, `node_modules` dev deps, apt cache | Only runtime + app artifact |
| **Security** | More packages → more CVEs | Minimal packages in final image |
| **Pull / deploy** | Large registry transfer, slow node cache warm | Smaller layers → **faster pull** to new nodes |
| **Compliance** | Harder to justify “what’s in prod” | Clear separation: build vs run |

**Honest note on “faster bringing up”:**

- Multi-stage mainly makes images **smaller**, so **pull + extract** is faster — that **speeds up deploys and scale-out** when the image isn’t cached on the node yet.
- **Container start time** (process exec to listening port) is mostly your **app + JVM warmup**, not multi-stage vs single-stage, if both use the same runtime command.
- Still fair to say multi-stage helps **overall time-to-ready** in dynamic environments (K8s pulling fresh images, CI/CD).

---

## 3. Sample A — Go (largest size contrast)

Build produces **one static binary**; final image can be **`scratch`** or **`distroless`** — no shell, minimal OS.

### 3.1 Normal (single-stage) — bloated

```dockerfile
# Single stage: toolchain stays in the image you run
FROM golang:1.22-bookworm

WORKDIR /app
COPY . .
RUN go build -o /server ./cmd/server

EXPOSE 8080
CMD ["/server"]
```

**Typical size:** hundreds of MB (full Go compiler + Debian base).

### 3.2 Multi-stage — small final image

```dockerfile
# ---- Stage 1: build ----
FROM golang:1.22-bookworm AS builder
WORKDIR /src
COPY go.mod go.sum ./
RUN go mod download
COPY . .
RUN CGO_ENABLED=0 GOOS=linux go build -o /out/server -ldflags="-s -w" ./cmd/server

# ---- Stage 2: runtime only ----
FROM gcr.io/distroless/static-debian12:nonroot
COPY --from=builder /out/server /server
USER nonroot:nonroot
EXPOSE 8080
ENTRYPOINT ["/server"]
```

**Typical final size:** often **~10–30 MB** for a small service (mostly the binary), vs **~800 MB+** for single-stage `golang:bookworm`.

